/// Program â€” the running program/invocation (ADR 0099 Â§2).
///
/// `Program` names *this running program*. It is the object that exists in every
/// execution context (run-mode, escript, connected) â€” unlike `Session`, which is
/// `nil` in compiled program code. All methods are class-side â€” `Program` has no
/// instances (same shape as `System` and `Console`).
///
/// It exposes `commandName` and the job-level half of the two-tier exit
/// (`exit` / `exit:`); `System halt:` is the node-level half.
///
/// ## Examples
/// ```beamtalk
/// // Under `beamtalk run`, there is no argv[0]:
/// Program commandName
/// // => "beamtalk"
/// ```
sealed typed Object subclass: Program native: beamtalk_program

  /// The invoked program's name as a `String`.
  ///
  /// Under a packaged escript it is the invoked filename; under `beamtalk run`
  /// there is no argv[0], so it is the literal `"beamtalk"`. Handy for usage and
  /// `--help` text; not load-bearing.
  ///
  /// Named `commandName` (not `name`) deliberately: `name` is the sealed
  /// reflective class-identity accessor (`Behaviour>>name`, a primitive used by
  /// `SystemNavigation` and the class machinery), so a class-side `name` on
  /// `Program` would shadow it and break reflection over the class universe.
  ///
  /// ## Examples
  /// ```beamtalk
  /// Program commandName
  /// // => "beamtalk"
  /// ```
  class sealed commandName -> String => self delegate

  /// End this program with status 0 â€” the job-level, safe exit. Does not return.
  ///
  /// In run-mode / escript (where the program owns the node) this exits the node
  /// with status 0. See `exit:` for the full contract and the process-boundary
  /// caveat.
  ///
  /// ## Examples
  /// ```beamtalk
  /// Program exit
  /// // => _
  /// ```
  class sealed exit -> Nil => self delegate

  /// End this program with status `code` â€” the job-level, safe exit (ADR 0099).
  /// Does not return.
  ///
  /// Where `System halt:` halts the whole VM, `Program exit:` ends *this program*.
  /// In run-mode / escript it exits the node with `code`; in a shared/connected
  /// workspace it ends only this session's job (pending the Session-termination
  /// hook, BT-2688) and leaves the node up.
  ///
  /// **Process boundary:** the run-mode / escript path is an immediate node
  /// halt, so it is effective from *any* process (the node is dedicated to this
  /// program). The connected-mode path (Phase 5) instead ends the session via a
  /// caught signal and so is effective only from the entry method's own call
  /// chain â€” there a spawned Actor returns a status to the entry method and lets
  /// *it* call `exit:`.
  ///
  /// ## Examples
  /// ```beamtalk
  /// Program exit: 2
  /// // => _
  /// ```
  class sealed exit: code :: Integer -> Nil => self delegate
